# Backend Able Can GQL Contract

This rule is a self-contained Ejtmaa permission contract. Do not mention, cite, compare against, or defer to external project names.

## Model Permission Gates

- Domain permission rules belong in the owning actor model as `type Ability`, not in requesters or GraphQL.
- Models with permissions must pass `Ability` into `Model<Attrs, CreationAttrs, Ability>`.
- `Ability` keys are domain nouns; each domain includes a mandatory `sub` union and only the target props needed by that permission.
- `can(...)` must return `this.iCan(...)`, throw stable message keys inside the test body, and never return booleans.
- `Able` is not boolean: success is `"CAN"`; denial is a code string or `{value, description}` when `visualMode` is used.
- Any query inside `can` that participates in an active mutation must receive the same transaction passed from the requester.

## Requester Enforcement Gates

- State-changing requesters must call `actor.can(..., {throwMode: true, transaction})` before the protected mutation when domain permission applies.
- Do not use `visualMode` for mutation enforcement.
- Do not duplicate reusable domain permission checks inline after calling `can`.
- Do not treat `await actor.can(...)` as a truthy/falsey boolean.

## GraphQL Exposure Gates

- Use GraphQL ability output when the UI needs backend-owned action availability or denial reasons.
- GQL/UI ability exposure must call the same model `can(...)` with `visualMode`.
- For current-actor action gates that depend on entity identity, expose the ability from `me` with explicit entity args and keep the entity read model separate. Do not move the same gate into an entity field unless the user explicitly approves an entity-owned ability surface.
- Prefer `me.abilities` or direct `me.*` ability fields for current-actor capabilities; use entity bridge extras only for bounded entity-specific ability fields that are not really `me` decisions.
- Ability fields must be side-effect free and must not perform writes.
- Avoid unbounded per-row `can` calls on root-many lists; if entity ability extras are added, the list must be bounded and required attrs/performance must be explicit.
- Ability SDL should use a shared `_Able { value: String!, description: String }` shape unless a local equivalent already exists.
- When SDL changes, keep generated backend types and frontend GraphQL mirrors (`website/` for customer, `cpanel/` for supervisor) synchronized through existing repo scripts/processes.

## Consistency Gates

- Requester `throwMode` enforcement and GraphQL `visualMode` display must use the same `can` rule.
- If GraphQL says an action is allowed but the requester denies it, the implementation is incomplete.
- If an action is always allowed and no UI decision/reason is needed, do not add a GQL ability field.
- Do not expose ability details for records outside the role/principal scope.
